04437nam a22006135i 9780887559389DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808875593897 a10.1515/97808875593892doi  a(DE-B1597)678845  a(OCoLC)1246177751  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA 4aE98.P99bH395 2022eb 7aHIS0060202bisacsh04a305.8970712231 aHay, Travis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInventing the Thrifty Gene :bThe Science of Settler Colonialism /cTravis Hay. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tUnderserviced and Overstudied -- tOn the Origins of Thrifty Genes -- tThe Operation of Being Civilized -- tStudied to Death -- tThe Marrow Thief -- tChief Josias Fiddler -- tThe Return of the Thrifty Gene -- tThe Grandfather Rocks of Josias Fiddler -- tJosias Fiddler’s Life and Legacy -- tAcknowledgements -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThough First Nations communities in Canada have historically lacked access to clean water, affordable food, and equitable health care, they have never lacked access to well-funded scientists seeking to study them. Inventing the Thrifty Gene examines the relationship between science and settler colonialism through the lens of “Aboriginal diabetes” and the thrifty gene hypothesis, which posits that Indigenous peoples are genetically predisposed to type 2 diabetes and obesity due to their alleged hunter-gatherer genes. Hay’s study begins with Charles Darwin’s travels and his observations on the Indigenous peoples he encountered, setting the imperial context for Canadian histories of medicine and colonialism. It continues in the mid-twentieth century with a look at nutritional experimentation during the long career of Percy Moore, the medical director of Indian Affairs (1946–1965). Hay then turns to James Neel’s invention of the thrifty gene hypothesis in 1962 and Robert Hegele’s reinvention and application of the hypothesis to Sandy Lake First Nation in northern Ontario in the 1990s. Finally, Hay demonstrates the way in which settler colonial science was responded to and resisted by Indigenous leadership in Sandy Lake First Nation, who used monies from the thrifty gene study to fund wellness programs in their community. Inventing the Thrifty Gene exposes the exploitative nature of settler science with Indigenous subjects, the flawed scientific theories stemming from faulty assumptions of Indigenous decline and disappearance, as well as the severe inequities in Canadian health care that persist even today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndigenous peoplesxHealth and hygienezCanada. 0aIndigenous peoplesxResearchzCanadaxHistory. 0aIndigenous peoplesxResearchzCanada. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxPublic opinion. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxSocial conditions. 0aRace relationszCanada. 0aSciencexSocial aspectszCanadaxHistory. 0aSciencexSocial aspects. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh  aCanadian healthcare.  aIndigeneous healthcare.  amedical racism.  asystemic racism.1 aFiddler, Teri Redsky, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755938940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887559389423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887559389/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles